title: COVID-19 pandemic in the United States
added: On October 2nd, 2020, President Trump tweeted that both he and First Lady Melania Trump tested positive for COVID-19 and will immediately quarantine, likely due to [[Hope Hicks]], a top Trump senior advisor, contracting it right before.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dawsey|first=Josh|last2=Itkowitz|first2=Colby|title=Trump begins quarantine as close aide Hope Hicks tests positive for coronavirus|language=en-US|work=Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/hope-hicks-close-trump-aide-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/2020/10/01/af238f7c-0444-11eb-897d-3a6201d6643f_story.html|access-date=2020-10-02|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Vella|first=Lauren|date=2020-10-01|title=Trump, first lady to quarantine after top aide tests positive for coronavirus|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/519281-trump-first-lady-to-quarantine-after-top-aide-tests-positive-for|access-date=2020-10-02|website=TheHill|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Mason|first=Jeff|date=2020-10-02|title=Trump starts "quarantine process" after aide Hope Hicks tests positive for coronavirus|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-hicks-int-idUSKBN26N0FV|access-date=2020-10-02}}</ref>

title: COVID-19 pandemic in the United States
added: In October, [[Bain & Company]] reported on the tumultuous changes in consumer behavior before and during the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref name=Bain /> Potentially permanently, they found acceleration towards [[e-commerce]], [[telehealth|online primary healthcare]], livestreamed gym workouts, and moviegoing via subscription television.<ref name=Bain /> Concurrent searches for both low-cost and premium products, and a shift to safety over sustainability, occurred alongside rescinded bans and taxes on single-use plastics, and losses of three to seven years of gains in out-of-home foodservice.<ref name=Bain>{{cite web|url=https://www.bain.com/insights/shaping-the-consumer-of-the-future/|title=Shaping the Consumer of the Future|date= September 23, 2020|vauthors= Faelli F, Rovit S, Apps C, Johns L|publisher=Bain & Company|accessdate=October 3, 2020}}</ref>

title: COVID-19 pandemic in the United States
added: According to a study published in ''[[Science Advances]]'', areas with higher levels of COVID-19 fatalities were less likely to support Trump and Republican candidates for Congress.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Warshaw|first=Christopher|last2=Vavreck|first2=Lynn|last3=Baxter-King|first3=Ryan|date=2020-10-01|title=Fatalities from COVID-19 are reducing Americans’ support for Republicans at every level of federal office|url=https://advances.sciencemag.org/content/6/44/eabd8564|journal=Science Advances|language=en|volume=6|issue=44|pages=eabd8564|doi=10.1126/sciadv.abd8564|issn=2375-2548}}</ref>
